    <p class="islet islet--light"> Note: as you can see, the early registers were identified by <em>Roman numeral</em>s (for example, XII) and later ones by <em>Arabic numerals</em> (for example, 12), but FreeBMD uses only Arabic numerals for searching (so a search for volume <em>12</em> would find volume <em>XII</em>).</p>
    <p>The Registers themselves are held by the <a href="https://www.gro.gov.uk/" target="_blank">General Register Office (opens in new window)</a> (GRO); and under current legislation only officials of the GRO are allowed to access them. You can buy a certified copy of an entry in the Registers from the GRO: for more details, see our page on [Ordering Certificates]("Ordering Certificates").</p>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="page">Page numbers</h2>
  <p class="islet islet--neutral">Civil Registration was set up as a ‘paper-based’ system. However, parchment (not paper) was used for index pages and — as part of a security system — every page was individually numbered and was bound into an index volume or into a register (as appropriate). Loose sheets of paper could be lost and were a security risk. So, confusingly, a <em>page number</em> has two possible meanings. If you wish to purchase a certificate, you need to quote a <strong>Page number</strong> — this is the number of the page in the GRO Register containing your record. FreeBMD transcribes pages of the GRO Indexes, so if you, for example, ask us to add a missing entry (that you see on the scan) to our database, you need to do that from the Entry Information page for the record on the <strong>Index Page</strong> immediately above the missing one. Sometimes, we need to clarify which type of page we are refering to, such as in the figure above. If we have not added a <em>clarification</em> of what we are referring to: <em>Page number </em>means <strong>Register Page number</strong>.</p>
    <p>The (Register) Page (or<strong> Page</strong>) is a number, possibly followed by a letter, that identifies the page in the Register containing the entry. You will need this page number, together with: the name of person for which you need a certificate, the <em>event,</em> when it happened, the District and the Volume, the year and quarter to uniquely identify an entry. You can use this “packet” of information, the <a href="#indexes">GRO Index Reference, described above</a> to order a certified copy of the entry in the Register (commonly known as a “certificate”).</p>
    <p>Entries on a page are generally not related, other than having been entered in registration-date-order at the same (Registrar’s) Registration District. The exceptions being for: [twins (in the birth Register)]("Searching &amp; associated FAQs#twin"), although they might appear on adjoining pages; [spouses (in the marriage register)]("Help with Marriages"]; and possibly victims of a multiple death event (in the deaths register), again they might appear on adjoining pages.</p>
  <p class="islet islet--neutral">The early indexes (1837 to 1851) appear to have a logical page-ordering sequence. For births, marriage and death registers: arranged by registration date and alphabetical ordering of Registration Districts within a Superintendent Registrar’s Registration District. For weddings ordering was by parish church (in alphabetical order, then Register Office weddings and Registrar-attended weddings (Non-Conformist weddings). FreeBMD does not carry out page-checks below the level of the Registration District, so this cannot be verified. After 1851, alphabetical-ordered by district can be seen in some volumes, but less so in others.</p>
<hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <h2 id="qualityControl"> Database quality control checking</h2>
    <p>FreeBMD updates its main database on an approximately 28-day cycle. During these updates, all the new entries that have been transcribed since the last update — together with any corrections made to the existing records — are incorporated into the database and made available for you to search.</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">As part of this update-cycle, all the entries have quality assurance checks and “possible error flagging”. These checks include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>is the District name consistent with the Volume number and are they valid for the date of that record?</li>
      <li>is the Page number within the range of “expected” Page numbers for that event (birth, marriage or death), District, Volume and quarter? If so, this will be shown …</li>
      <p> <mark> This can't be answered yet as neither test2 nor test3 have implemented this. - PC</mark> </p>
      <li>has the record has been “double-keyed”? If so, this will be shown …</li>
      <p> <mark> This can't be answered yet as neither test2 nor test3 directly state this has been done (but it might it be inferred: need to check). - PC</mark>
       </p>
     <li>are there any “suspect” District, Volume or Page “flags” for the record? If so, this will be shown …</li>
       <p> <mark> This can't be answered yet as neither test2 nor test3 have implemented this. - PC</mark> </p>
    </ul>
        <p>During this process, various tables are generated that show the correspondences between Districts, Volumes and Pages. If you would like to read more about these correspondences as well as the different spellings of District names over time, please see our page on [Registration Districts]("Registration Districts").</p>
